{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"A plugin whose manifest is missing a required field is rejected before any code from that plugin is executed.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Pairwise tournament: Unit vs Integration -> Integration wins because the failure boundary is the handoff between manifest validation and module-loading/execution (must prove rejection prevents import side effects), not just one pure validator function. Integration vs System -> Integration wins because behavior text only requires local loader/module wiring; no real network, subprocess, or OS-specific primitive is required. Rejection gate: higher levels were rejected because the behavior contains no AI/ML step and no multi-agent sequence.","test_description":"Create a temporary plugin directory with one plugin whose manifest.json omits a required field and whose entry module writes a sentinel file or mutates a global on import. Run the real loader over that directory. Assert (1) loader reports manifest validation failure, and (2) sentinel side effect never occurs, proving plugin code was not executed.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"This test needs real wiring between validator and importer; a unit test of validator alone cannot catch accidental import-before-validate regressions.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.22,"Integration":0.71,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When plugin A declares a dependency on plugin B, plugin B's onLoad hook is called before plugin A's.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Pairwise tournament: Unit vs Integration -> Integration wins because this failure appears when dependency resolution output is handed to lifecycle execution across multiple plugins. Integration vs System -> Integration wins because ordering can be validated in-process with local fixtures; no subprocess/network/real external infra is needed. Rejection gate: Agentic/Workflow are disqualified since behavior is deterministic plugin orchestration with no model decisions.","test_description":"Set up two test plugins A and B where A depends on B. Instrument each onLoad to append its name to a shared call log. Run the loader and assert call log order is [\"B\",\"A\"].","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Requires resolver + scheduler + hook runner together; single-function tests can miss integration ordering bugs.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.18,"Integration":0.77,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When two plugins each declare a dependency on the other, the loader reports the cycle and loads neither.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Pairwise tournament: Unit vs Integration -> Integration wins because behavior requires both cycle detection and enforcement in loading (\"reports the cycle and loads neither\"). Integration vs System -> Integration wins because this is in-process graph + loader behavior, not OS/network/subprocess behavior. Rejection gate: no behavior text indicates AI/ML output dependence or multi-agent chaining.","test_description":"Create plugins A and B with mutual dependencies. Give each entry module/onLoad a detectable side effect. Run loader and assert (1) cycle error is reported, and (2) neither plugin side effect appears (neither imported/loaded).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Catching 'detected but still loaded' regressions needs resolver-to-executor integration, beyond a pure cycle algorithm unit test.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.24,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"A plugin's onLoad hook is only invoked after the plugin's entry module has been imported and executed.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Pairwise tournament: Unit vs Integration -> Integration wins because the bug boundary is sequencing between module import execution and lifecycle hook invocation across loader components. Integration vs System -> Integration wins since Node import and hook call order can be validated in one process with local fixtures; no external infra needed. Rejection gate: behavior text is deterministic sequencing, with no AI/ML decision or multi-step agent pipeline.","test_description":"Create a plugin whose entry module sets exported/shared state during import, and whose onLoad asserts that state is already set (or records timestamps/order markers). Run loader and assert onLoad sees post-import state, proving import execution happened first.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"A unit test on hook runner alone cannot verify real import-before-hook sequencing.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.74,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When a plugin throws an error during its onLoad hook, the loader continues initializing the remaining plugins that do not depend on it.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Pairwise tournament: Unit vs Integration -> Integration wins because failure isolation depends on interaction among dependency graph evaluation, error handling, and scheduler continuation across multiple plugins. Integration vs System -> Integration wins because this can be reproduced with in-process plugin fixtures and thrown exceptions; no subprocess/network/OS primitive is required. Rejection gate: no text indicates real model output dependence, and this is not a multi-agent workflow.","test_description":"Create plugins: F (throws in onLoad), D (depends on F), and I (independent). Run loader and assert (1) F failure is reported, (2) I still loads successfully, and (3) D does not load because of dependency on failed plugin.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Needs end-to-end loader orchestration across plugins; unit-level exception tests miss dependency-aware continuation behavior.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.16,"Integration":0.79,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0}}]}
